title: Psychology Study Group, Task 3 Auto - Function of Behavior
authors: EDUC 3100 Assessment Module

~~~~

Introduction [id=fba2_intro_section]
------------

::fba2_introduction [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Introduction"]

Annie: Okay, so... bad news about Johnny. The positive reinforcement stuff from last time works for getting him to his room — sticker chart, toys before bed, all of that. But the second my roommate says "time for bed," he takes off running and laughing. Every single time. [face=concerned]

JJ: Running? Like, around the house? [face=awe]

Annie: Through the house, behind the couch, under the dining table. At first she'd just call his name from the doorway. Now she's literally sprinting after him. He knocked a lamp off the end table last week. [face=fear]

JJ: Sounds like he's trying to get a reaction out of her. Classic attention-seeking, right? [face=explaining]

Annie: Maybe? One night she tried not reacting — just stayed in the kitchen, didn't chase. He got wilder and wilder until she gave in and went after him. Now she's resorted to bribing — she promised him extra screen time last night just to get him to stop. He eventually wears himself out, but she texted me afterward and just said, "I want this to be over." [face=concerned]

Lin: Hmm. Let's not jump to conclusions about why he's doing it — not yet. But it does sound like whatever's happening, the current approach isn't working. [face=serious]

Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_intro]
---------------------

Lin: Actually, this reminds me of something from class. One of the things we learned was that whenever you need to intervene with a behavior, the intervention has to address the function of the behavior. [face=serious]

Annie: The function? Like... what the behavior does? [face=hectic]

JJ: Oh! I think I sort of remember this. It's why the kid is doing it — like I said, Johnny's probably doing it for the attention.

Lin: That's the right idea — function is about why the behavior keeps happening. But let's not assume we already know Johnny's. I remember Lianne telling us it's better to try to actively recall something than to just passively look it up. You understand it better that way.

JJ: Okay, fair. I think I can write a prompt to get AI to check our answer, at least. That way we'll know if we're on the right track. [face=explaining]

::fba2_ai_function_def [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Define Function of Behavior"]

--- wait @fba2_ai_function_response.value ---

Annie: JJ thinks it's attention. What's your guess? [face=smile]

::
<ChoiceInput id="fba2_johnny_function_prediction_inline">
  <Markdown>Maybe...</Markdown>
  <Distractor> Attention            </Distractor>
         <Key> Escape               </Key>
  <Distractor> Access to tangibles  </Distractor>
  <Distractor> Sensory              </Distractor>
</ChoiceInput>
::

--- wait @fba2_johnny_function_prediction_inline.submitCount > 0 ---

Annie: Okay, so the function is basically the reason the behavior keeps happening — what the kid is getting out of it. That makes sense. So we need to figure out WHY Johnny is running away at bedtime. [face=smile]

JJ: Right, and I still think it's attention. He's laughing, she's chasing — that's a social interaction he's creating. [face=explaining]

Lin: Maybe. But let's learn the framework first before we commit to an answer. If we just go with our gut, we might design the wrong intervention. [face=serious]

Introducing Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_concepts]
---------------------------------

::fba2_function_notes [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Lin's Notes"]

Lin: Here are my notes from class. Based on what we covered, the four main functions of behavior are attention, escape, access to preferred activity or object, and sensory.

JJ: And my notes say the function always refers to a type of reinforcement — positive or negative. Wait, that's key, right? It's always reinforcement, never punishment?

Annie: Positive and negative reinforcement! We went over that last time. I remember the gist, but I'm a little fuzzy on the details...

Lin: I took a picture of some examples our TA Lianne wrote on the board. Let me pull those up.

Review of Previously Learned Concepts [id=fba2_reinforcement_review_section]
--------------------------------------

Lin: Before we go further, let's make sure we actually remember the basics. Let's work through a few of these until we get, say, 3 in a row right. [face=serious]

JJ: Good call. Otherwise we might just be fooling ourselves! [face=smile]

::fba2_reinforcement_review [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Review Reinforcement Concepts"]

--- wait @fba2_reinforcement_mastery.completed ---

Teaching Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_teaching]
------------------------------

JJ: Okay, I definitely needed that refresher. Some of those were trickier than I expected.

Lin: Me too. Now, Lianne also mentioned something else in class — she said that if the function is attention or tangibles, it usually involves positive reinforcement. If the function is escape, it typically involves negative reinforcement. And for sensory, it can be either one.

Annie: My brain would really benefit from seeing all of that in one place. Like a chart or something. I bet AI could help with that.

JJ: Actually, I already tried writing a prompt for this. My first version was something like "Create a chart showing the four functions of behavior with examples of how each relates to positive and negative reinforcement." [face=explaining]

Lin: And how did that go?

JJ: Honestly? The results looked good at first glance, but when I checked them carefully, the AI had filled in cells that shouldn't have entries — with examples that sounded plausible but were actually misleading. I had to revise the prompt several times. [face=concerned]

Annie: So what did you end up with? [face=awe]

JJ: I basically had to spell out which combinations are valid and tell it to leave incompatible cells blank. It was like the AI was so eager to be helpful that it made stuff up to fill every cell. [face=smile]

::fba2_ai_function_chart [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Create Function Chart with AI"]

--- wait @fba2_ai_chart_response.value ---

Lin: That chart makes the relationships much clearer. [face=smile]

JJ: Especially because two cells are blank! Escape involves removing something aversive, so it doesn't combine with positive reinforcement, which is about adding something. And tangibles are about gaining something, so they don't combine with negative reinforcement, which is about removal. [face=explaining]

Annie: Okay, that's a good explanation of the chart. But we won't really learn it just by reading it — we need to try making examples ourselves, right?

Your Turn: Own Examples [id=fba2_own_examples_section]
------------------------

Annie: Let's each come up with our own examples for each function. That's the only way I'll know if I actually understand this.

Lin: Right. For each function, try to think of a situation involving positive reinforcement, and another involving negative reinforcement. Some of those combinations are going to be tricky — that's the point.

::fba2_own_examples_attention [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Your Examples: Attention"]

