--- wait @fba2_pos_reinforcement_sensory.value && @fba2_neg_reinforcement_sensory.value ---

Annie: Okay, some of those were really hard. Did anyone else have trouble with escape and positive reinforcement? I kept going in circles. [face=hectic]

JJ: Yes! And I think that's because those combinations don't actually work — which is exactly what the blank cells in the chart were telling us. The struggle was the lesson!

Lin: Right. But didn't we learn about punishment too?

JJ: Yeah, I was wondering about that. Can punishment be a function?

Check for Understanding - Punishment [id=fba2_punishment_check]
--------------------------------------

Annie: Hmm, before we look up the answer, what do you all think? Why might punishment NOT be a function of behavior?

::fba2_predict_punishment [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Predict: Why Not Punishment?"]

--- wait @fba2_punishment_confidence.value ---

Annie: That makes sense! Functions are about what the person gains from the behavior — what keeps it going. Punishment by definition decreases behavior, so it can't be the reason a behavior continues. [face=smile]

Practice with Functions [id=fba2_function_practice]
------------------------

JJ: Okay, this is starting to click for me. But I feel like I need more reps before I trust myself with it.

Lin: Same. Practice is the only way to make this stick.

Annie: I asked AI to generate some examples for us to test ourselves on. Let's see how we do.

::fba2_function_sorting [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Practice: Identify Functions"]

