ABCs of Behavior [id=fba2_abc_section]
-----------------

Annie: Okay, I think I'm getting the hang of functions. But didn't Lianne say there was something else we needed to do to actually figure out the function? Like, a process? [face=explaining]

Lin: Right — we need to look at what comes before the behavior and what comes after it. The antecedent, the behavior, and the consequence.

JJ: The ABCs! A for antecedent, B for behavior, C for consequence.

Annie: Oh right, the professor said "It's as easy as learning your ABCs!" I remember thinking that was a little corny but also really helpful. [face=smile]

Teaching ABCs with AI [id=fba2_abc_teaching]
----------------------

Annie: Let's get AI to help us see the ABCs in action with some examples.

::fba2_ai_abc_diagrams [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Create ABC Diagrams with AI"]

--- wait @fba2_ai_abc_response.value ---

Scaffolding ABCs [id=fba2_abc_scaffold]
-----------------

JJ: I tried making one of these myself. Here's what I came up with for an escape example. [face=explaining]

::fba2_abc_ref_escape

JJ: The Antecedent is the yellow box — that's what happens before the behavior. Here, the teacher gives a difficult task... [face=explaining]

Lin: Which leads to the Behavior in the blue box — the student puts their head down.

Annie: And the Consequence is the green box? The task is removed or delayed... so the student basically got out of doing the work.

JJ: Exactly. The teacher gave a hard task, the student put their head down, and then the teacher either gave up and removed the task, or just pushed it to homework. Either way, the student escaped.

Lin: And that's why the behavior continues — it works. The student learned that putting their head down gets them out of hard tasks. That's escape maintained by negative reinforcement.

Checking ABCs Understanding [id=fba2_abc_check]
----------------------------

Lin: Let's apply this framework to Johnny's situation now.

::fba2_abc_johnny [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Apply ABCs to Johnny"]

--- wait @fba2_abc_johnny_explanation.value ---

JJ: Okay, here's what I got. The antecedent is Johnny running around the house. The behavior is the roommate chasing him. And the consequence is he eventually goes to bed. [face=explaining]

Lin: Hold on — whose behavior are you analyzing? [face=serious]

JJ: ...Johnny's? [face=concerned]

Lin: You just described the roommate's chain. Johnny running is the antecedent for *her* behavior. We need to start from Johnny's perspective — what triggers *his* running? [face=serious]

JJ: Oh — right. The antecedent is the roommate saying "time for bed." The behavior is Johnny running. And the consequence is... the roommate chases after him and bedtime gets delayed. [face=explaining]

JJ: So the function is attention, right? He runs away laughing, she chases him — he's getting a big social reaction out of the whole thing. [face=smile]

Lin: Think about what the consequence actually achieves. Yes, the roommate chases him — but what's the *outcome*? What changes in Johnny's world because he ran? [face=serious]

JJ: He gets chased... the roommate is paying attention to him...

Annie: But also he doesn't go to bed. The running works — bedtime gets pushed back every time.

Lin: Exactly. The laughing and the chasing are what it looks like on the surface. But the consequence that's actually maintaining the behavior is that bedtime gets delayed. He runs, and he successfully avoids going to bed. That's escape, not attention. [face=serious]

JJ: Oh. OH. So the laughing is just how he does it, but the function — the reason it keeps happening — is because it gets him out of bedtime? [face=awe]

Lin: Right. If it were attention, you'd expect the behavior to stop once he got the attention. But it doesn't — he keeps running until bedtime is effectively over. The attention is incidental. The escape is the function.

Annie: That's actually a really important distinction. It looks like one thing but it's actually another. [face=concerned]

Lin: And remember the chain JJ wrote first — the one from the roommate's perspective? That wasn't actually wrong. It was a different behavior chain. [face=calm]

JJ: Wait, what? [face=awe]

Lin: Think about it. The roommate hears Johnny running — that's her antecedent. She chases — that's her behavior. And eventually he goes to bed and the chaos stops — that's her consequence. The relief of it being over reinforces the chasing. [face=serious]

JJ: So Johnny is escaping bedtime, and the roommate is escaping Johnny-running-around-the-house? [face=awe]

Lin: They've conditioned each other. Remember when she tried ignoring him? He got wilder, she caved — and she never tried ignoring again. Johnny shaped her into chasing, then bargaining, then screen time bribes. And she shaped Johnny into running by making it work every time. [face=serious]

Annie: A six-year-old has operant-conditioned a college student. I am NOT telling her that. [face=smileLOL]

::fba2_johnny_function [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Identify Johnny's Function"]

--- wait @fba2_johnny_function_choice.submitCount > 0 ---

