Intervention Planning [id=fba2_intervention_section]
----------------------

JJ: Okay, so now we need to figure out an actual intervention. We know the function of Johnny's running-away behavior is escape — not attention, as I learned the hard way. So what do we do about it? [face=smile]

Lin: Here's what my textbook says about escape-maintained behavior.

  _"Escape is used to get away from something aversive or not preferred. Changing **antecedent conditions** is key to intervening when the function of behavior is escape."_

Annie: That's interesting — last time we focused mostly on consequences, but the textbook is saying antecedent strategies are really important for escape. We kind of skipped over that before.

Checking Intervention Understanding [id=fba2_intervention_check]
------------------------------------

::fba2_intervention_strategies [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Sort Intervention Strategies"]

Lin: Here's what my Child Development textbook says about generating interventions. We need strategies for the problem behavior of "not going to bed on time."

JJ: What if we break this into two pieces? Let's think about antecedent strategies first — things we can do before bedtime to prevent escape. Then we'll tackle consequence strategies separately. Otherwise this is going to get overwhelming. [face=explaining]

--- wait @fba2_escape_strategies_done.value ---

Annie: Okay, I think I'm getting the hang of this! [face=smile]

Annie: But wait — not all of those strategies were about escape. Some of them were for attention or sensory. We should make sure we're narrowing down to strategies that actually address the escape function, right?

JJ: Good catch! Let's ask AI to help us brainstorm more interventions, this time specifically focused on escape as the function. Then we can build our actual plan.

Annie: My roommate is going to be so relieved when we figure this out. [face=smile]

