Escape Plan Review [id=fba2_escape_plan_review]
-------------------

::fba2_escape_plan_display [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Review Escape Plan Details"]

JJ: There's a lot in here. Not everything makes equal sense for Johnny's specific situation, but I really like the timer idea — using a timer to show when each routine step begins and ends. That's a solid antecedent strategy. [face=explaining]

Lin: I agree. And on the consequence side, I think the strategy of ignoring escape behavior — not chasing, not providing attention or reinforcement during the escape — makes a lot of sense based on what we've learned.

Annie: Me too. What parts stand out to you?

--- wait @fba2_plan_likes.value ---

Checking Understanding of Plans [id=fba2_plan_check]
--------------------------------

::fba2_sensory_plan_check [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Check: Why Not the Sensory Plan?"]

JJ: This sensory plan looks completely different from the escape one.

Annie: I know, but some of the sensory ideas are genuinely good strategies. Calming music before bed, a predictable sensory environment... wouldn't those help any kid? [face=explaining]

Lin: They might help in general — but remember what we learned. The intervention has to address the function. Johnny's function is escape, not sensory. A weighted blanket isn't going to solve the problem if the reason he's running away is to avoid going to bed. It's like treating a headache with a bandaid — the bandaid isn't bad, it's just not targeting the right thing. [face=serious]

Annie: Okay, that's a good way to put it. Nice strategies, wrong function. [face=smile]

--- wait @fba2_sensory_check_choice.submitCount > 0 ---

